The demand was too high, and a few of the Eagle marked 19s made it stateside before production finally caught up. They came with the older, better "frying pan" slide finish. Less than 1K rounds fired. Comes with Israeli Meprolite night sights and an awesome $200 stipple job. Maritime cups. Books, box, test cartridges, etc. Larry Vickers baseplate extended magazine release, and slide catch installed. title: For Sale/Trade:  M1 Garand
postcontent: I have an M1 Garand I'd like to sell.This is a "Danish return" rifle.  This rifle saw service in WW2 and has a Springfield made October 1943 dated receiver.  After the war it was sent to Denmark as war aid, where it received a new VAR barrel (known for their accuracy) as well as a mix of Italian made parts (Beretta and Breda), which is "correct" for this type of rifle.  Metal finish has wear but has no rust or visible pitting.  Stock has character with wear typical for its age.  Barrel is in nice condition with good rifling and no rust or pitting, muzzle wear measures at 2 and throat wear is also 2.  Has had no corrosive ammo through it while I've owned it.  Will come with a cotton sling and 5 clips.  Also included is paperwork from the Garand Collector's Association documenting muzzle and throat wear as well as other details of various parts.Not desperate to part with it, but Id like to maybe sell it to pay down some debts.Not really wanting to trade right now, but might take partial trade of other surplus rifles (no mosins), maybe a G42, 9mm Glocks, M&P 2.0 pistols, Walther PPQ, possibly similar pistols in 9mm or 45.  Only 40 I would look at would be an M&P 2.0 in the std size or the 5 inch model.  Maybe bulk 9mm ammo. title: For Sale/Trade:  Marlin Model 1893 Lever Action Rifle w/post 1904 Special Smokeless Steel
postcontent: Marlin Model 1893 Lever Action Rifle w/post 1904 Special Smokeless SteelThis is a beautiful, super clean, no cracks in wood, excellent condition Marlin Model 1893 Lever-Action Rifle with the post 1904 Special Smokeless Steel marking that is roll-stamped on the left side of the barrel.  The barrel, magazine, forearm cap, hammer, trigger & crescent steel buttplate have a blued finish.  The receiver, bolt & lever are case hardened with vivid case colors.  The straight grain walnut stock & forearm have a varnish finish.  The top of the barrel is roll-stamped: "Marlin Fire-Arms Co. New Haen, Ct, USA, Patented Oct 11 1887 April 2, 1889. August 1, 1893" in two lines ahead of the rear sight and "Special smokeless Steel" is boldly roll-stamped on the left side of the barrel below the rear sight.  The caliber designation "30-30" is stamped on the top of the barrel between the rear sight and the receiver.  "Marlin Safety" is roll -stamped on the top of the receiver in script letters with small foliate designs on either end of the marking.  The servial number is stamped across the bottom of the receiver.  The upper receiver tang is roll-stampedwith the designation "Model/<1893>," with arrows on either side of "1893." In 1905 the tang marking was changed to "Model/93," the tang & barrel markings indicate that this rifle was probably manufactured c. 1904-05.  The Model 1893 rifle was the first Marlin lever-action rifle manufactured for smokeless powder cartridges.  The rifle retains at least 99% plus of the original blue finish on the marrel, magazine, forearm cap, loading gate, hammer and buttplate.  The receiver, bolt & lever have virtually all of the firey, vivid, original case colors.  The stock & forearm are in excellent condition & retains ALL of the original varnish finish.  The walnut wood is in near perfect condition.  The barrel & receiver markings are crisp.  The bore is bright.  This is an extraordinary example of a Marlin Model 1893 Lever-Action Rifle.
